<h2>Why Couples Seek Therapy</h2>
<p>Couples enter therapy for many reasons: persistent conflict patterns that never fully resolve, emotional distance that has grown over years, infidelity and trust repair, major life transitions (new baby, job loss, relocation), differing visions for the future, and sexual difficulties. They also enter therapy proactively — pre-marital couples seeking to establish healthy patterns before problems develop.</p>

<p>What most couples have in common when they reach a therapist is that they've been trying to solve the same problems with the same approaches for a long time. Couples therapy works because it introduces a third perspective, teaches new skills, and interrupts the negative cycles that maintain distress.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Approaches for Couples</h2>

<h3>EFT (Emotionally Focused Therapy)</h3>
<p>EFT is the most evidence-based couples therapy approach, with decades of research showing strong and durable outcomes. It's grounded in attachment theory — the understanding that adult romantic relationships are fundamentally attachment bonds, and that relationship distress typically involves one or both partners feeling unsafe or disconnected.</p>
<p>EFT identifies the recurring negative interaction cycle (pursue-withdraw, criticise-defend) and traces it back to the underlying attachment fears driving each partner's behaviour. By accessing and expressing these deeper emotions (fear of being unloved, fear of rejection), partners can respond to each other's vulnerability rather than reacting to the surface behaviour. This creates new, secure interactions.</p>

<h3>Gottman Method</h3>
<p>The Gottman Method is based on four decades of research on what predicts relationship satisfaction and stability. It addresses specific problematic interaction patterns ("The Four Horsemen" — criticism, contempt, defensiveness, stonewalling), builds "love maps" (knowledge of each other's inner worlds), and develops shared meaning and friendship as the foundation of relationship health.</p>

<h3>CBT for Couples</h3>
<p>Cognitive-behavioural couples therapy addresses the beliefs and interpretations partners bring to their relationship ("They don't care about me," "This will never change") and the behaviours that maintain distress. It teaches communication skills, problem-solving, and conflict resolution tools.</p>

<h2>How Online Couples Therapy Works</h2>
<p>Online couples therapy is delivered via video call with both partners present. Sessions are typically 50–90 minutes. Research comparing online and in-person couples therapy shows comparable outcomes — the modality matters less than the approach and the therapeutic relationship.</p>

<p>Practical considerations: both partners need to be in a private location where they can speak freely. Some couples participate from the same location; others (particularly for co-parenting therapy after separation) participate from different locations. The therapist manages the session dynamics either way.</p>

<h2>What Online Couples Therapy Cannot Replace</h2>
<p>Couples therapy is not appropriate when there is ongoing domestic violence or coercive control. In these situations, joint therapy can be unsafe and counterproductive. Individual therapy for the person experiencing abuse is appropriate first.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>My partner is resistant. Can I start alone?</strong><br/>
Yes. Individual therapy can address relationship issues, help you develop new approaches, and sometimes motivates the reluctant partner to participate. Many couples begin with one partner in individual therapy.</p>

<p><strong>How many sessions will we need?</strong><br/>
EFT typically runs 8–20 sessions. The Gottman Method varies. Some couples resolve a specific problem in 6–8 sessions; others benefit from longer-term work. Most see meaningful improvement within 10–12 sessions.</p>

<p><strong>Is it too late for therapy?</strong><br/>
It depends. EFT research shows high success rates even with severely distressed couples. However, the decision to stay in the relationship matters more than the degree of distress — both partners need to be willing to work.</p>

<p><strong>Do you focus on the problem or the past?</strong><br/>
Effective couples therapy focuses primarily on the present relationship dynamic rather than relitigating the past. Understanding history is useful; the goal is changing how partners interact now.</p>

